e":"Deg\"","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Reginald  , often preferred by bearers of that name for use in almost all situations, but rarely actually bestowed as a baptismal name."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ieuan \" Deg\" ap Tudur was born about 1370, in Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom as the son of Tudur ap Ieuan. He had at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"ABT    1370–":"umbes 1370–Surnud","1370–Female":"1370–Surnud","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1404–Female":"1404–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1404":"1404","1330":"1330","ABT    1370":"umbes 1370","1370":"1370","of,Talybolion cmt,Anglesey,Wales":"Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom","{Cadrod Hardd}":"Chadrūd, Herāt, Afganistan"},"fi":{"ABT    1370–":"noin 1370–Kuollut","1370–Female":"1370–Kuollut","1370–Male":"1370–Kuollut","1404–Female":"1404–Kuollut","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1404":"1404","1330":"1330","ABT    1370":"noin 1370","1370":"1370","of,Talybolion cmt,Anglesey,Wales":"Anglesey, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","{Cadrod Hardd}":"Chadrūd, Herāt, Afganistan"},"fr":{"ABT    1370–":"environ 1370–Décédé","1370–Female":"1370–Décédée","1370–Male":"1370–Décédé","1404–Female":"1404–Décédée","1330–Male":"1330–Décédé","1404":"1404","1330":"1330","ABT    1370":"environ 1370","1370":"1370","of,Talybolion cmt,Anglesey,Wales":"Anglesey, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","{Cadrod Hardd}":"Chadrūd, Herāt, Afghanistan","lifeSummary":"Ieuan \" Deg\" ap Tudur est né environ 1370, à Anglesey, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni, fils de Tudur ap Ieuan. Il a eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"ABT    1370–":"um 1370–Verstorben","1370–Female":"1370–Verstorben","1370–Male":"1370–Verstorben","1404–Female":"1404–Verstorben","1330–Male":"1330–Verstorben","1404":"1404","1330":"1330","ABT    1370":"um 1370","1370":"1370","of,Talybolion cmt,Anglesey,Wales":"Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom","{Cadrod Hardd}":"Chadrūd, He